introd. to that Odel, Sat. 1. 6. 42, A. P. 371 ‘diserti Messallae! Who Pedius was is uncertain. The Seholiasts say that he and Corvinus were brothers. This may be illustrated by, or may be due to, v. 85 ‘te, Messalla, tuo curn fratre,' where they annotate ‘ sc. Publi- eola,’ but see on that verse. That the two families were connected is known from Pliny (N. H. 35. 7) who states that Q. Pedius, the nephew of C. Julius Caesar, was married into the family of Messalla. Their grandson was a deaf- mute who, by Messalla's advice, was taught the art of painting. This is all that is known. It has been conjectured, but on no further grounds, that Q.
